Mamming: Corona mass infection: 174 harvesters infected
After a Corona mass infection on a large vegetable farm in Mamming, Lower Bavaria, almost 500 people are under quarantine and are no longer allowed to leave the farm.
A security service is monitoring the curfew.
A total of 174 harvesters tested positive for the corona pathogen Sars-CoV-2 during the serial examination, as the district office Dingolfing-Landau announced on Saturday evening.
"In order to prevent further spread, we unfortunately have to take this step to protect the population," explained District Administrator Werner Bumeder (CSU).
Previously, seven employees had already been infected at the plant - this was the reason for the row test.
The farm is a large vegetable farm that grows strawberries, cucumbers, cabbage and beet - but only the cucumbers for pickling jars.
Mamming is a rural community with a good 3300 inhabitants not far from Dingolfing with its large BMW plant.
Bumeder appealed to citizens to remain calm: "According to our information, it is a closed circle of people."
Infected and non-infected employees have been separated on the farm, and the area is now surrounded by a barrier fence.
The Greens and the SPD placed joint responsibility on the state government.
The two opposition factions accused Prime Minister Markus Söder (CSU) and his cabinet of neglecting to control the accommodation of seasonal workers.
"This can take bitter revenge if such local infection events spread and regional lockdowns have to be ordered," said Jürgen Mistol, the parliamentary manager of the Green Party.
The SPD has a similar view: "We have already called for a special control program for farms with harvest workers as well after the Corona outbreak in the Wiesenhof slaughterhouse in mid-May," said environmental expert Florian von Brunn.
"Especially the hygiene conditions at the workplace and the living conditions must be sharply controlled from our point of view.
This obviously did not happen."
The outbreak had come "with notice," he said.
