Discuss abolition of the 50+1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thinking about abolishing the 50+1 rule.
"German soccer should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates a fait accompli," Grindel told Bild am Sonntag.
He stressed, "For the clubs that are most likely to pose a threat to Bayern and Dortmund, the 50+1 rules don't work anyway: see Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In this respect, there is no getting around the debate as to whether it is not necessary to make it easier for clubs that want to break into this phalanx to involve investors."
But he said he doubted whether there was a willingness in the German Football League to allow majority stakes, which are prohibited in the Bundesliga by the 50+1 rule.
"It remains a legal risk to draw investment fences around the Bundesliga as a business location in a single European market," Grindel said.
The former DFB boss sees a danger that "attempts to ensure more competitive balance in the Bundesliga will only end up weakening the competitiveness of our top clubs at European level, but will not lead to more excitement in the championship."
Even an equal distribution of TV money would not achieve a decisive effect, he said.
"FC Bayern makes a turnover of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund of 500 million and RB Leipzig of 300 million.
So the differences are already immense among the top three clubs alone.
The other 15 clubs have an average budget of 130 million," the 58-year-old explained.
Looking at the past, Grindel feels betrayed.
"Unfortunately, there have been people who noticed this mistake and leaked it to the press instead of addressing me about it," Grindel said of accepting an expensive watch that led to his resignation in April 2019.
"That has already bothered me a lot on a human level".
He had received the gift, worth around 11,000 euros, from a Ukrainian official.
"I committed a compliance violation, and it was right to draw the consequences," Grindel said.
"I dealt with the ominous watch gift in a completely transparent and guileless manner.
After all, many people in the DFB knew about it."
He never "made a secret of the gift," the 58-year-old assured.
"You might call that naive, but in any case this form of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption."
