North Sea wind farms deliver a good 21 percent more electricity
In the first six months of the year, wind farms on the German North Sea fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period last year, the grid operator Tennet announced in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for transmitting North Sea electricity to the mainland and forwarding it through the German power grid.
Wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of Tennet's grid area, fed in another 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
In total, wind power from the North Sea and Baltic Sea thus comes to 13.73 TWh, compared to just over 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
Wind harvesting at sea thus accounts for almost 19 percent of total wind power in Germany; that's about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms provide higher generation capacity
In addition to wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind power results from higher generation capacities because new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind farms in the North Sea were all running at full power at the same time, they could mathematically generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this; according to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is expected to increase to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore grid connections by then," said Tennet Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, wind farms can't reach their full capacity even offshore, but reach about 40 percent.
The record day so far this year is Jan. 2, when North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, the equivalent of three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
