Heil to examine other industries after meat industry
The Corona crisis again brought to light the conditions in parts of the meat industry.
Tightening of the law is imminent.
But are they legal - and will they remain so?
Federal Labor Minister Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to review other industries after the strict regulations against abuses in the meat industry that are now planned.
"We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for each industry if necessary," Heil told the Deutsche Presse-Agentur in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
Following the mass corona outbreak at meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the federal cabinet plans to pass a bill by Heil this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use outside personnel for slaughtering, cutting and meat processing.
In addition, the use of contract workers and temporary workers is to be banned there.
Employers' President Ingo Kramer told dpa: "Hands off a general restriction of work contracts and temporary workers if you don't want to completely strangle the economy."
Contracts for work and services are, for example, for large areas of the skilled trades, the construction industry and plant engineering compellingly the basis for their value creation at the customer.
"The misconduct of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument."
Heil assured, "My goal is not to ban work contracts everywhere in the German economy."
He added that work contracts make sense.
"If an industrial company commissions a craftsman to install a security system, that is a perfectly normal contract for work and services."
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary work in its sector alone to be unconstitutional.
It is inexplicable why different labor laws should apply in the future to portioning and packaging cheese than to sausage, it says in a statement on the proposed law, as reported by the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday).
According to the statement, a ban would increase the consumer price by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
In many cases, Eastern European employees from work contract companies worked in the industry, according to the results of an audit by the NRW labor protection administration, sometimes 16 hours a day.
Often they had no breaks.
Wages were withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also found that the situation regarding housing for employees was often miserable.
Heil said a relatively harsh law had already come into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, "tricky constructions" had circumvented it.
"Now it must be fundamentally cleaned up".
The politician announced, "In the Occupational Health and Safety Act, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, there are also measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher inspection quotas for occupational health and safety or clear criteria for shared accommodation."
The draft submitted to dpa includes amendments to the law on safeguarding employee rights in the meat industry and to the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Consumer Protection Minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) believes more intensive controls are necessary.
"I would like us to be able to do even more controls in many supervisory areas: Food controls, animal welfare, all kinds of things, for example, animal transports," Nonnemacher said Sunday on the RBB program "Brandenburg aktuell."
But for more controls also more personnel places are necessary.
