Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the threatened penalties and court rulings, drivers continue to step on the gas in countless illegal races on Baden-Württemberg's roads: last year and in the first four months of this year, police in the southwest have already recorded more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparative figures for previous years, but the speeders are increasingly making work for the judicial authorities: at the public prosecutor's offices between Constance and Mannheim, a total of 155 preliminary proceedings were conducted for illegal racing in 2018, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year up to the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, according to the Interior Ministry's response to a question from the state parliamentary SPD.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or fled from the police - which is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speeders caught and also asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed and 15 prison sentences handed down since 2018.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, because of the quite a few tragic accidents and lawsuits in past years, other motorists are reacting more sensitively than before and are reporting more frequently, a ministry spokesman said.
Highway 8 is particularly popular with speeders, who repeatedly slow down traffic there to make room and use the open stretch for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught doing this near Kirchheim unter Teck, and three months earlier there were as many as 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is most popular "race track
On the A81, the police even register more races than on any other federal highway.
An attempt is being made there with a speed limit to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped-out sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers escape to Germany to speed because of the high penalties for speeding and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit should not be limited to a few stretches of road: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on highways," says Martin Rivoir, the traffic expert for the SPD's state parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you weren't still legally allowed to drive here and there at 200 kilometers per hour and more."
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: "Anyone who flouts all the rules in such a way and puts not only their own life but also the lives of other road users at risk can hardly be reached with reason.
ADAC calls for stronger police action
For the ADAC, however, this is not enough: "We assume that speeders will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, head of the traffic and environment department at ADAC Württemberg.
He calls for additional and also tougher controls on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed trial of strength turns into painful and momentous seriousness: since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died nationwide in the races, two of them bystanders in a nighttime crash in Stuttgart's city center and one in Gerlingen.
There, two young men allegedly engaged in a car race in November.
One of the vehicles went off the road, crashed into a garden wall and came to rest on its side, killing the 18-year-old passenger.
21 other people were injured in the races over the past two years.
Stricter penalties, however, are not necessary, according to Interior Minister Thomas Strobl: "Legislative need for action to sanction illegal motor vehicle racing more severely is not seen," the Interior Ministry paper says.
