World Heritage in Potsdam: Party in the New Garden broken up
Potsdam - On Friday evening, about 40 young people celebrated a party in the New Garden.
The accumulation had been dissolved at 20.48 o'clock by the precinct drivers of the Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation (SPSG), the Foundation told PNN inquiry.
The young people had then left the park.
On Saturday evening, some young people had then played rugby in the New Garden.
The meadow had been cleared by precinct drivers, said SPSG spokesman Frank Kallensee on Sunday.
Again and again it comes to illegal celebrations in the parks
In the parks of the foundation it comes again and again to accumulations, with which the distance and hygiene rules Covid-19-Umgangsverordnung are not kept.
At the end of June, there was a celebration with about 300 people in the Babelsberg Park, and a week later about 150 people celebrated in the New Garden.
Even without a Corona ordinance, the parks are closed at nightfall.
According to the park regulations, camping on the meadows is prohibited, and there are only a few exceptions.
The foundation has been complaining for some time that visitors were leaving more and more trash behind and destroying protected biotopes.
In Berlin, meanwhile, illegal park parties have reached another dimension.
In the Hasenheide in the Neukölln district, 5000 people celebrated an illegal techno party on Sunday night.
The event was broken up by the police.
Austria: Mass tests after Corona outbreak in tourist resort
Authorities have responded to a Corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang with hundreds of tests.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, according to provincial authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
According to the report, many of those infected are young trainees in tourism businesses, but at least one vacation guest also tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism employees were asked to stay in their accommodations on Saturday evening.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations here and there" of bookings, the head of the Wolfgangsee tourism association, Hans Wieser, told dpa.
There have also been isolated guests who have left early, he said.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist destination in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, about a third of the guests are German.
On Friday, the first infections had become public knowledge.
The head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behavior of the trainees, who had celebrated in several pubs and may have been infected.
"We all liked to do that in our youth," he told radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The tourism board launched an information campaign to make young employees aware of the dangers of Covid-19.
Hundreds of employees, vacationers and locals were then tested starting Saturday.
Additionally, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang as of July 15 were contacted.
The outbreak brings back memories of the Austrian ski and party resort of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a center of Corona spread throughout Europe during the early stages of the pandemic.
In total, more than 1500 people are currently infected with the virus in Austria.
The main areas of new infections are Vienna and Upper Austria.
Premier League: Man United and Chelsea qualified for Champions League
London (dpa) - English soccer record champions Manchester United are returning to the Champions League after a year's absence.
The Red Devils secured third place in the table on the final matchday of the Premier League with a 2-0 (0-0) win over direct rivals Leicester City.
The Foxes will now have to settle for the Europa League because Chelsea FC passed them by and also qualified for the top flight in fourth place.
In the battle against relegation, Aston Villa was able to celebrate.
Manchester United took the lead through a penalty kick by Bruno Fernandes (71st minute).
After a red card for Leicester City in injury time, Jesse Lingard (90.+8) scored the final goal.
Chelsea, FC Bayern's opponent in the Champions League round of 16, won 2-0 (2:0) against Wolverhampton Wanderers in parallel thanks to Mason Mount (45.+1) and Olivier Giroud (45.+4).
"It means a lot to me," said coach Frank Lampard, who is also in the FA Cup final against Arsenal in his first season as Chelsea coach.
Also benefiting from Chelsea's win over Wolverhampton was Tottenham Hotspur, which edged past Wolves with a meager 1-1 (1-0) draw at Crystal Palace to start sixth in the Europa League.
Aston Villa won the long-distance duel with Watford FC and AFC Bournemouth, but had to tremble for a long time at West Ham United.
Jack Grealish's late lead (84th) was immediately cancelled out by Andrej Jarmolenko (85th).
The 1:1 (0:0) was enough, however, because Watford lost 2:3 (1:3) at Arsenal.
The club, which fired three coaches during the season, is relegated after five first division years.
Just like Bournemouth, which could not save itself with a 3:1 (2:1) at Everton FC.
In the end, they were one point short.
Liverpool FC, which has been the English champion since the end of June, secured a club record with a 3-1 (1-1) win at Newcastle United.
99 points are the highest the Reds have ever scored in a soccer season.
Coach Jürgen Klopp and his team just missed the points record in English soccer.
The best mark is held by Manchester City with 100 points in the 2017/18 season.
After Newcastle took the lead in the first minute, Virgil van Dijk (38th), Divock Origi (59th) and Sadio Mané (89th) turned the game around for Liverpool on Sunday.
"It's been an extraordinary season for this wonderful club," scorer van Dijk said after the game, "that should spur us on to defend the title.
It will be difficult."
Satisfied should also be the Premier League bosses in the end.
Due to the coronavirus crisis, soccer operations in England were interrupted from March 13 to June 17.
In the meantime, there were even discussions about premature termination or playing the remaining games on neutral ground.
In the end, however, the season was played to a close without any particular incidents - albeit, as in Germany, without spectators in the stadiums.
Arrests and violence at demonstrations against Netanyahu
Protests in Israel against head of government Netanyahu are becoming more violent.
Violent clashes have occurred during the night.
Israeli police violently cracked down on participants in a demonstration against the right-wing conservative head of government Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem on Sunday night.
Twelve people were arrested for participating in riots, police spokesman Micky Rosenfeld said.
Among other things, the police used water cannons to break up the rally.
A total of about 6,000 people had gathered near Netanyahu's official residence on Saturday evening, according to media reports.
They were protesting unemployment, corruption and Netanyahu's handling of the Corona crisis.
The protesters beat drums, blew horns and called on Netanyahu to resign.
Participants in a counter-demonstration who supported Netanyahu were also arrested, the news site "ynet" reported.
People also demonstrated in many other locations in Israel, including outside the head of government's private villa in the coastal city of Caesarea and in a park in Tel Aviv.
One man was arrested near Tel Aviv on suspicion of spraying pepper spray from a moving car at protesters on the side of the road, according to police.
Another man was arrested after a knife attack on a demonstrator in the south of the country.
The demonstrator had been lightly wounded in the neck.
There have been several demonstrations against Netanyahu in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv recently.
The rallies accompany the corruption trial against the head of government.
Recently, Netanyahu has also been criticized for his handling of the Corona crisis.
Among other things, he has been accused of hasty easing and a lack of preparation for a second Corona wave.
The Corona crisis has taken a heavy toll on the country's economy.
The unemployment rate recently exceeded 20 percent.
The number of new infections with the corona virus in Israel recently rose to ever new record levels.
Accident near Ahlen (NRW) - Transporter crashes into car - nine injured - Ruhrgebiet - Bild.de
Ahlen - A rear-end collision caused nine light injuries on Saturday afternoon on the B58 near Ahlen.
A car driver was traveling with her two children (3, 5) in the direction of Beckum.
The police: "Presumably she had braked suddenly because she wanted to turn".
The driver of a Mercedes transporter, who was driving behind her, must have seen this too late.
He crashed into the back of the van.
Three occupants in the car and six in the van were slightly injured in the accident.
Several ambulances took them to a nearby hospital.
North Korea seals off border town after Corona suspect case
North Korea has so far considered its own measures to ward off the corona virus a "shining success."
Now, for the first time, the country is reporting a suspected case.
Because of a first official suspected corona case in the country, North Korea has completely sealed off a major city for fear of disaster.
Despite the strictest epidemiological defense measures over the past six months, "the malignant virus may have been introduced into the country," state media reported.
A state of emergency had been declared for the region around the border city of Kaesong.
The communist leadership declared the highest level of alert.
If the suspected case is confirmed, it would be the first official case of infection with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
North Korea said it had not registered a single infection so far and described its defensive measures as a "shining success."
The claims were doubted abroad.
The disease symptoms were reportedly detected in a "runaway" who illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on July 19.
The person had absconded to South Korea three years ago and had now returned across the border.
There was initially no confirmation from South Korea of the border crossing within the four-kilometer-wide military buffer zone, most of which is still mined.
South Korea's military, however, acknowledged the possibility of an illegal border crossing into North Korea as high, according to reports by the national news agency Yonhap.
Investigations were running to this to some persons.
North Korea said it called an emergency meeting of the Workers' Party Politburo, chaired by strongman Kim Jong Un, on Saturday over the suspicion.
The "dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive disaster."
Kim had already ordered on Friday as a preventive measure to "completely blockade Kaesong and isolate each district and the region from others," the statement added.
The person involved, as well as all people in Kaesong who had had contact with him, had been quarantined, it said.
According to the statement, the party's central military commission will investigate the "runaway case" as well as the behavior of the military unit responsible and impose harsh punishment if necessary.
According to estimates, about 300,000 people live in Kaesong.
