After much delay, Tim Zimmermann starts the new season
After a delay of almost half a year, Tim Zimmermann will start his premiere season in the ADAC GT Masters on July 31.
Before the league of super sports cars can start regular operations, the first test drives were now scheduled.
For Zimmermann, the main focus was on getting to know his Lamborghini Huracan GT3 better.
For a long time, the Corona crisis prevented Tim Zimmermann from tackling his first service drive in the new Lamborghini Huracan from Grasser Racing.
Under special hygienic conditions this was now possible.
The 23-year-old from Langenargen did his first laps at the Lausitzring and was able to get used to his premiere in the GT3 car.
"There are already a few things that are different from the Porsche from the previous season," says Zimmermann.
"With the ABS, for example, you have to take the corners differently.
But it was really a lot of fun."
Zimmermann also had fun with Steijn Schothorst, with whom he will share his orange sports car in the GT Masters.
Despite being only 25 years old, the Dutchman is already experienced in GT racing and was able to help his new teammate in many ways.
"After all, I'm not a beginner in motorsport, but every new series also brings new challenges," Zimmermann says.
"Steijn and I get on brilliantly and we also made enormous progress from session to session at the Lausitzring."
That's exactly where - at the Lausitzring - the GT Masters will also hold its first race.
Starting on July 31, the 33 supercars will race through the Lausitz.
Zimmermann, who is one of 15 series newcomers, knows the track, however.
He was last a guest at the Motodrom in 2015.
"It worked out quickly and I didn't have to get used to the track very much," says Zimmermann, who competes for the Friedrichshafen-based Graf Zeppelin racing team.
"The Lausitzring has many fast passages that you have to hit perfectly to be fast."
How fast Zimmermann really is then will be revealed in two weeks.
"Of course, the teams play a little poker during the tests," he says.
"In the end, however, we are very satisfied and are looking forward to the first weekend at the Lausitzring."
The race in Brandenburg will be the start of a packed calendar.
Seven races are scheduled between now and the beginning of November.
The current status is that no spectators will be allowed - but there will be a celebrity guest.
In mid-August at the Nürburgring, ex-Formula 1 driver Niko Hülkenberg will take to the GT wheel.
