The British government's decision to quarantine holidaymakers in Spain for two weeks after their return has, according to press reports, caught the country's transport minister cold.
According to the report, Grant Shapps is currently on vacation in Spain, of all places, while his colleagues at home decided on the measure on Saturday.
Because of the Corona numbers rising again in Spain, the Cabinet in London deleted the country from the list of those countries from which entry is possible without quarantine requirements.
The new regulation applies from today, Sunday, so Shapps will also have to quarantine after his return.
In Austria, the government has also imposed quarantine measures for returnees.
But the regulation applies to those who are just on the deadline vacation, only from Saturday, August 1, and was not introduced overnight.
Spain, by the way, is considered in Austria until now as one of the "safe countries" for which no quarantine is needed in Austria.
