"But apparently no one bothered to let Grant Shapps know".
Less than a month after the end of the Corona emergency in Spain and the expiration of the strict curfew, the infection figures in the country are rising again.
Virologists blame nightlife in particular for the renewed spread.
Spain is one of the favorite vacation destinations of the British.
From not necessary Reisens on the Spanish mainland the British government advises at present, the Canaries and Balearen particularly popular with British holiday-makers are excluded from it.
To date, more than 272,000 infections with the novel coronavirus and more than 28,000 deaths have been recorded in Spain.
Russia: Navy Day: Putin announces hypersonic weapons for warships
Russian President Vladimir Putin has announced on the occasion of his country's Navy Day that warships will be equipped with state-of-the-art hypersonic weapons.
These weapons, unique in the world, would expand the combat capabilities of Russia's naval forces, Putin said Sunday in St. Petersburg at the central naval parade.
The Defense Ministry also provided information on successful tests of the Zirkon hypersonic missile built for the Navy, according to the Interfax agency.
The hypersonic weapons have a speed of sound many times greater than the speed of sound, about 343 meters per second.
They are considered weapons of the future.
Underwater tropedeo continues to be built
Construction also continues on the Poseidon nuclear-tipped underwater torpedo, it said.
The planned naval drone is designed to destroy coastal targets.
The president, who himself also rode in a military boat, said that 40 new ships would be commissioned this year alone at the various fleet units of the world's largest country.
Russia has a coastal area larger than any other country in the world.
For 300 years, the navy has reliably protected Russia, Putin said at the day celebrated by sailors nationwide.
Naval forces in many other Russian coastal locations also celebrated Navy Day with parades.
In Syria, where Russia is fighting alongside strongman Bashar al-Assad, the military demonstrated strength at an arms display in the Mediterranean port of Tartus.
Ammunition was also fired there.
On display in a video released by the Defense Ministry were not only warships, including a submarine, but also combat helicopters and jets.
Hurricane "Hanna" reaches Texas: Help hampered because of Corona
Washington - The first hurricane of this season over the Atlantic has made landfall in Texas.
Life-threatening flooding, strong winds and heavy rains now threatened parts of the U.S. state, the National Hurricane Center of the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) announced Sunday night (local time).
Governor Greg Abbott declared a state of emergency for numerous counties.
The Corona pandemic rampant in Texas complicates the work of aid workers, Abbott said further, according to U.S. media.
Evacuees urged to use caution
"Any hurricane is a tremendous challenge," Abbott said, according to the Houston Chronicle newspaper.
Referring to the hurricane in Texas, he added, "That challenge is complicated and exacerbated when you consider that it is sweeping through an area that is the most Covid-19-affected area in the state."
According to Johns Hopkins University, about 5,000 people have died so far in Texas alone as a result of the Corona pandemic.
Abbott urged people who would have to leave their homes to be cautious.
They should not disregard practices "we have become accustomed to," such as wearing masks, the governor said, according to the CBS network.
It was important for everyone to keep their distance, he said.
For that reason, he said, hotel rooms have been made available in some locations.
In addition, it should be tested in emergency shelters on Corona, he said.
Damage had initially been reported only from the coastal town of Port Mansfield.
Storm warning withdrawn again
With wind speeds of up to 150 kilometers per hour, "Hanna" had made landfall on Padre Island just off the Texas coast, according to authorities.
The tropical storm had previously been upgraded to the lowest level one hurricane.
A storm surge warning had initially been issued for the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent and was later withdrawn.
Authorities expected weakening as "Hanna" moved further inland and headed toward northeastern Mexico.
"Douglas" moves toward Hawaii
In the Pacific Ocean, Hurricane "Douglas" was headed toward Hawaii Sunday night with winds of about 150 kilometers per hour.
However, the hurricane center expected it to weaken further.
According to the forecast, it should be near Hawaii's largest islands on Sunday (local time) - then as a storm just below the hurricane threshold.
Over the Atlantic, NOAA expected an above-average active hurricane season this year, according to a May forecast.
From June to the end of November, up to ten hurricanes can be expected, of which up to six could become very strong hurricanes, the agency had said.
On average, there are six hurricanes per year over the Atlantic, three of which develop into major storms.
Given available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and Caribbean, the probability of a normal season is only 30 percent, and that of a below-average season is only 10 percent, it said at the time.
U.S. President Donald Trump wrote via Twitter that his administration was closely monitoring the storms and was in contact with the affected states.
