Formula 1 needs a special rule to crown its world champion
Since it is not possible to race on the required number of continents, the FIA has to improvise in order to award the world championship titles.
All races in the Americas, meanwhile, have been canceled.
Race calendar becomes more and more concrete
The race calendar for the current Formula 1 season continues to take shape.
In addition to the ten Grand Prix confirmed so far, three more race tracks were added during the week.
In October, races are to be held at the Nürburgring in Germany and Portimão in Portugal.
On the first of November, Lewis Hamilton and Co. will be fighting for world championship points at the traditional Italian race track in Imola.
As things stand, this means that the 2020 race calendar will comprise 13 rounds.
"We are delighted that we continue to make great progress in finalizing our plans for the 2020 season," said Formula One boss Chase Carey.
A total of 15 to 18 races are expected to be completed in the premier class of motorsport during this extraordinary season.
Formula 1 plans to conclude its season in Asia.
The final race calendar is to be fixed and published in the coming weeks.
Before the races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December, which have already been officially targeted, media reports suggest that there could still be appearances in Vietnam and Malaysia at the end of November.
Regulations require races on three continents
However, Formula 1's regulations require at least races on three continents for the world championship to be awarded.
Even if, as is currently planned, races are only held on two continents, there is to be one world champion.
With the help of a special rule, the FIA wants to award the titles, citing "exceptional circumstances" due to the coronavirus pandemic.
The traditional start of the season in Australia in March had to be cancelled at short notice due to the emerging corona crisis.
A return to the continent this year is not an option.
In addition, Formula 1 will not be visiting America this year.
Cancellation meets with criticism in Brazil
Due to the tense Corona situation, the races in Canada, the U.S., Mexico and Brazil will not take place.
"We look forward to being back with them next season," Carey explained.
The cancellation of the Americas races was met with criticism, particularly in Brazil: "The cancellation did not come as a surprise to us, but we cannot accept the reasons for it," said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in São Paulo.
For example, he said, the infection figures in the São Paulo area are much lower than in other regions of Brazil.
Moreover, the concerns of some teams about not wanting to race in Brazil would not justify a cancellation.
They were prepared for the required safety measures, he said.
Greta Thunberg: Evil look against Donald Trump went around the world
Greta Thunberg spoke about her encounter with US President Donald Trump.
Greta Thunberg was a guest on Stephen Colbert's popular latenight show via video chat and revealed in an interview what was on her mind during her encounter with Donald Trump.
Climate activist Greta Thunberg was a guest on a popular US latenight show via video chat.
Among other things, she talked about her fight against the powerful of the world.
The teenager also talked about her famous "evil eye" when she met Donald Trump.
New York City - In the past two years, climate activist Greta Thunberg drew attention to herself with her tireless efforts for the "Fridays For Future" movement.
Now she spoke on a popular latenight show about her plans for the future, as well as her encounter with U.S. President Donald Trump at the UN Climate Summit last year.
Latenight host Stephen Colbert welcomed the 17-year-old Thunberg to your show on Tuesday and conducted a lengthy interview with the Swede.
In it, she talked not only about her fight against climate change, but also about her conflict with the world's powerful.
"There are some things that surprised me," she opined.
"How far people will go to shift the focus away from the climate crisis" shocked her, she said.
"Everything from organized hate campaigns to threats just because a group of kids take to the streets" is what she experienced, she said.
She finds heads of state and leading politicians who mock her on social media or even try to silence her "funny" because the reactions show her "because they have no other response."
Things got particularly interesting toward the end of the interview when Greta Thunberg was asked about a famous scene in which she gave U.S. President Trump a bitter look.
At the 2019 UN Climate Summit in New York, for which the actvist sailed across the Atlantic, her expressive look was caught on camera and has since been seen by countless people on the Internet.
The short clip was turned into a GIF, or animated image, which ultimately became one of the most used images for Trump opponents.
But what did the 17-year-old think about the U.S. president at that moment?
In response to Stephen Colbert's relatively open question, she replied only briefly and dryly: "To be honest, I don't think that needs any further explanation.
The experienced satirist Colbert probably didn't expect this quick-witted answer and disappeared from the picture laughing for a moment.
She was remembered by many at the climate conference for her "How dare you?" speech on the principles of climate protection.
