Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green dead.
His life was like a roller coaster ride: after a rapid rise with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly up again.
Now blues rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Genius guitarist, drug junkie, cult devotee: the co-founder of the band Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members announced in an official statement on Saturday, with a further statement to be announced in the coming days.
Top musicians such as Peter Frampton paid tribute to Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
Mick Fleetwood, in an emotional response, spoke of a "monumental loss" for all former and current members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
Fleetwood, a drummer, and Green, a guitarist, had formed the now long legendary band in London in 1967; his dreamy instrumental hit "Albatross" remains unforgotten to this day.
The musician's life ("The End Of The Game," "In The Skies") resembled a roller coaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac, Green experienced a rapid ascent - but the band then celebrated its greatest successes without him.
Among other things, there is said to have been a dispute because Green wanted to donate all the group's profits to charity.
He began to appear in wide robes and with a large crucifix.
Psychological problems are also said to have played a role.
Just three years after forming, Green left the band in 1970.
A social decline followed.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
For a long time, Green was treated in a psychiatric ward.
During much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He reportedly lived on the streets at times, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent time on an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 to a working-class Jewish family in London's Bethnal Green neighborhood.
At a young age, he became fascinated with U.S. blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
He learned his first guitar chords at the age of eleven.
At the age of 15, the teenager started playing guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to be on stage as the lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
Not long after, he was hired to replace his idol Eric Clapton in the Bluesbreakers.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green formed Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 with fellow Bluesbreakers members Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross," composed by Green, gave the group its first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green couldn't cope with the media hype, and his experiments with the drug LSD became increasingly extreme.
He later commented on his life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that happened to me in life was the drugs - the best thing was to land a number 1 hit.
Toward the end of the decade, Green surprisingly achieved respectable success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac, meanwhile, was riding a wave of success without him in a new formation.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not manage a major comeback until 1996, when he relaunched with a group of musician friends.
At the time, the British "Daily Telegraph" spoke of a rock star who had returned to earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band broke up in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his smooth sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
